February 2020)\n|6\n|Friend of case 6\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|22\n|6 February 2020\n|46\n|Male\n|Korean\n|Naju\n|[[Chosun University]] Hospital, [[Gwangju]]\n|No\n|(Infection in Domestic)\n|Discharged (15 February 2020)\n|1\n|Brother of case 16\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|23\n|6 February 2020\n|57\n|Female\n|Chinese\n|Seoul\n|National Medical Center, [[Seoul]]\n|Yes\n|23 January 2020\n|Discharged (29 February 2020)\n|23\n|\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|24\n|6 February 2020\n|28\n|Male\n|Korean\n|Asan\n|National Medical Center, [[Seoul]]\n|Yes\n|31 January 2020\n|Discharged (27 February 2020)\n|0\n|Passenger on board the evacuation flights from Wuhan\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|25\n|9 February 2020\n|73\n|Female\n|Korean\n|Siheung\n|[[Seoul National University Bundang Hospital]], [[Seongnam]]\n|No\n|(Infection in Domestic)\n|Discharged (5 March 2020)\n|12\n|Mother of case 26\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|26\n|9 February 2020\n|51\n|Male\n|Korean\n|Siheung\n|Gyeonggi Provincial Medical Center Anseong Hospital, [[Anseong]]\n|No\n|31 January 2020 (Guangdong)\n|Discharged (8 March 2020)\n|12\n|\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|27\n|9 February 2020\n|37\n|Female\n|Chinese\n|Siheung\n|Gyeonggi Provincial Medical Center Anseong Hospital, [[Anseong]]\n|No\n|31 January 2020 (Guangdong)\n|Discharged (7 March 2020)\n|38\n|Wife of case 26\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|28\n|10 February 2020\n|30\n|Female\n|Chinese\n|Goyang\n|Myongji Hospital, [[Goyang]]\n|Yes\n|20 January 2020\n|Discharged (17 February 2020)\n|1\n|Friend of case 3\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|29\n|16 February 2020\n|82\n|Male\n|Korean\n|Seoul\n|[[Seoul National University Hospital]], [[Seoul]]\n|No\n|(Infection in Domestic)\n|Discharged (March 2020)\n|117\n|Friend of case 83\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|30\n|16 February 2020\n|68\n|Female\n|Korean\n|Seoul\n|[[Seoul National University Hospital]], [[Seoul]]\n|No\n|(Infection in Domestic)\n|Discharged (March 2020)\n|27\n|Wife of case 29\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|}\n\n===18 February \u2013 29 February===\n{{anchor|Daegu outbreak}}\n[[File:2020 coronavirus cases in South Korea.svg|350px|thumb|left|[[Epidemic curve]] of COVID-19 in South Korea]]\n\nOn 18 February, South Korea confirmed its 31st case in Daegu, a member of the [[Shincheonji Church of Jesus the Temple of the Tabernacle of the Testimony|Shincheonji]] religious organisation. The patient continued to go to gatherings of Shincheonji days after showing symptoms, which are typically held with people in very close proximity and include physical contact of the members. Many of the patient's close contacts would turn out to be infected, triggering a drastic escalation of the South Korean spread of confirmed cases of [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]] infection.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Farrer|first=Martin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/22/coronavirus-south-korea-sees-huge-jump-cases-china-hubei-wuhan-outbreak-|title=Coronavirus: South Korea cluster drives huge rise in cases|date=22 February 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=4 March 2020|last2=agencies|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305220400/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/22/coronavirus-south-korea-sees-huge-jump-cases-china-hubei-wuhan-outbreak-|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=fp20200227/>\n\nOn 19 February, the number of confirmed cases increased by 20. On 20 February 70<ref name=\"ThomReut_SKorea_zombie\" /> new cases were confirmed, giving a total of 104 confirmed cases, according to the KCDC. According to ''[[Reuters]]'', KCDC attributed the sudden jump of 70 cases linked to \"Patient No. 31\", who had participated in a gathering in [[Daegu]] at the Shincheonji Church of Jesus the Temple of the Tabernacle of the Testimony.<ref name=\"ThomReut_SKorea_zombie\" />\n\nOn 20 February, the streets of Daegu were empty in reaction to the Shincheonji outbreak. A resident described the reaction, stating \"It's like someone dropped a bomb in the middle of the city. It looks like a zombie apocalypse.\"<ref name=\"ThomReut_SKorea_zombie\" /> The first death was reported<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/south-korea-reports-first-coronavirus-death-infections-linked-church-rise-n1139821|title=South Korea reports first coronavirus death as infections linked to church rise|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=21 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310234601/https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/south-korea-reports-first-coronavirus-death-infections-linked-church-rise-n1139821|archive-date=10 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> in a mental ward of Cheongdo Daenam Hospital in [[Cheongdo County]]. According to the mayor of Daegu, the number of suspected cases as of 21 February was 544 among 4,400 examined followers of the church.<ref>{{cite web |title=\uc2e0\ucc9c\uc9c0 \uad00\ub828 \ud655\uc9c4\uc790 76\uba85\uc73c\ub85c \ub298\uc5b4...\ub300\uad6c \uad50\uc778 \uc758\uc2ec\uc790\ub9cc 544\uba85 |publisher=Chosun.com |date=21 February 2020 |url=https://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2020/02/21/2020022101558.html |access-date=21 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226102756/https://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2020/02/21/2020022101558.html |archive-date=26 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The hospital was suspected as the source of the present outbreak after it was visited by a woman who became the second fatal case of South Korea on that day. Upon investigation, it was determined that the infection had spread to that hospital through a funeral ceremony attended by members of the church.<ref name=\"b82186\" /><ref name=\"koreabiomed\">{{cite news |last1=Lee |first1=Han-soo |title=COVID-19 patients soar to 204 in Korea |url=http://www.koreabiomed.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=7489 |accessdate=21 February 2020 |work=Korea Biomedical Review |date=21 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226102842/http://www.koreabiomed.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=7489 |archive-date=26 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAll South Korean military bases were on lockdown after tests confirmed three soldiers to be positive for the virus.<ref name=\"b82186\">{{Cite news|url = https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51582186|title = South Korea virus 'emergency' as cases increase|work = BBC News|date = 21 February 2020|access-date = 21 February 2020|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200307193706/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51582186|archive-date = 7 March 2020|url-status = live}}</ref> Airlines cut connections and cultural schedules were being canceled due to fears of further spread.<ref>{{cite news |title=Airlines to suspend more flights over coronavirus |url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200221000249 |accessdate=21 February 2020 |work=Korea Herald |agency=Yonhap |date=21 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221023912/http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200221000249 |archive-date=21 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Song |first1=Seung-hyun |title=Foreign artists delay concerts in Korea due to spread of COVID-19 |url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200221000554 |accessdate=21 February 2020 |work=Korea Herald |date=21 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221190026/http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200221000554 |archive-date=21 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[United States Forces Korea]] raised the alert level from low to moderate and cut off non-essential travel to and from USFK Daegu.<ref name=\"MT\">{{cite web|url = https://www.militarytimes.com/news/your-military/2020/02/19/us-forces-korea-imposes-new-coronavirus-protections-after-uptick-in-s-korea-cases/|title = US Forces Korea imposes new coronavirus protections after uptick in S Korea cases|date = 19 February 2020|access-date = 23 February 2020|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200306190234/https://www.militarytimes.com/news/your-military/2020/02/19/us-forces-korea-imposes-new-coronavirus-protections-after-uptick-in-s-korea-cases/|archive-date = 6 March 2020|url-status = live}}</ref> USFK Daegu's school facilities were closed and non-essential personnel were ordered to stay at home while any visitors going there were not allowed to enter.<ref name=\"MT\" /> USFK announced that the widow of a retired soldier who was in Daegu was diagnosed to be positive for the virus on 24 February.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stripes.com/news/pacific/usfk-dependent-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-putting-military-on-high-alert-in-south-korea-1.620023 | title=USFK dependent tests positive for coronavirus, putting military on high alert in South Korea | access-date=25 February 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226102852/https://www.stripes.com/news/pacific/usfk-dependent-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-putting-military-on-high-alert-in-south-korea-1.620023 | archive-date=26 February 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> [[Camp Humphreys]] enacted virus detection protocols, including temperature checks and raised the alert level to high.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.businessinsider.com/us-forces-korea-high-alert-for-coronavirus-after-positive-test-2020-2 | title=US troops in Korea are on high alert for coronavirus after widow of retired soldier tests positive | access-date=25 February 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227153541/https://www.businessinsider.com/us-forces-korea-high-alert-for-coronavirus-after-positive-test-2020-2 | archive-date=27 February 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> On 26 February, an American soldier based at Camp Carroll was diagnosed to be positive and was quarantined away from bases via off-base housing unit<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-southkorea/us-soldier-infected-as-south-korea-coronavirus-cases-rise-above-1260-idUSKCN20K045| title=U.S. Soldier infected as South Korea coronavirus cases rise above 1,260| newspaper=Reuters| date=26 February 2020| access-date=26 February 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303231232/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-southkorea/us-soldier-infected-as-south-korea-coronavirus-cases-rise-above-1260-idUSKCN20K045| archive-date=3 March 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> with contact tracing done that showed his movements to Camp Walker.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/south-korea-coronavirus-cases-continue-to-soar-towns-sealed-off-in-northern-italy-2020-02-25 | title=First U.S. Soldier in South Korea tests positive for coronavirus; towns sealed off in northern Italy | access-date=26 February 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305134342/https://www.marketwatch.com/story/south-korea-coronavirus-cases-continue-to-soar-towns-sealed-off-in-northern-italy-2020-02-25 | archive-date=5 March 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAs of 22 February, among 9,336 followers of the church, 1,261 reported symptoms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mohw.go.kr/react/al/sal0301vw.jsp?PAR_MENU_ID=04&MENU_ID=0403&page=1&CONT_SEQ=353047&SEARCHKEY=TITLE&SEARCHVALUE=%EC%BD%94%EB%A1%9C%EB%82%98%EB%B0%94%EC%9D%B4%EB%9F%AC|script-title=ko:\ucf54\ub85c\ub098\ubc14\uc774\ub7ec\uc2a4\uac10\uc5fc\uc99d-19 \uad6d\ub0b4 \ubc1c\uc0dd \ud604\ud669 (2\uc6d4 22\uc77c 09\uc2dc)|first=|date=22 February 2020|url-status=live|title=Archived copy|access-date=22 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226102804/http://www.mohw.go.kr/react/al/sal0301vw.jsp?PAR_MENU_ID=04&MENU_ID=0403&page=1&CONT_SEQ=353047&SEARCHKEY=TITLE&SEARCHVALUE=%EC%BD%94%EB%A1%9C%EB%82%98%EB%B0%94%EC%9D%B4%EB%9F%AC|archive-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> At the time, 169 confirmed cases involved the same church and another 111 came from the Cheongdo Daenam Hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.go.kr/|script-title=ko:\uc9c8\ubcd1\uad00\ub9ac\ubcf8\ubd80|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention Korea|title=Archived copy|access-date=22 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130022550/http://www.cdc.go.kr/|archive-date=30 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> 23 February saw another 123 cases with 75 being from Shincheonji<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030&act=view&list_no=366303&tag=&nPage=1 |title= 123 additional cases have been confirmed |author= <!--Not stated--> |date= 23 February 2020 |website= [[Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] |publisher=  |access-date= 24 February 2020 |quote=  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200223090022/https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030&act=view&list_no=366303&tag=&nPage=1 |archive-date= 23 February 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref> and 24 February saw 161 additional cases with 129 being from the same religious group. Over 27,000 people have been tested for the virus with 19,127 negative results.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030&act=view&list_no=366323&tag=&nPage=1 |title= 161 additional cases have been confirmed |author= <!--Not stated--> |date= 24 February 2020 |website= [[Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] |publisher=  |access-date= 24 February 2020 |quote=  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200224201926/https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030&act=view&list_no=366323&tag=&nPage=1 |archive-date= 24 February 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nOn 24 February, 15 countries imposed travel restrictions to and from South Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/asia/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-02-24-20-hnk-intl/h_303decf2bc32dd08ce587a7e9f3efafd|title=15 countries have travel restrictions on South Korea|last=|first=|date=24 February 2020|website=CNN|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224070457/https://edition.cnn.com/asia/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-02-24-20-hnk-intl/h_303decf2bc32dd08ce587a7e9f3efafd|archive-date=24 February 2020|access-date=24 February 2020}}</ref> It was also reported that a senior health official overseeing the COVID-19 efforts in Daegu tested positive and was also a member of Shincheonji.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3052129/coronavirus-infected-health-official-leading-south |title= Coronavirus: infected health official leading South Korea's fight against Covid-19 is member of Shincheonji Church of Jesus doomsday cult |last= Park |first= Chan-kyong |date= 24 February 2020 |website= [[South China Morning Post]] |publisher=  |access-date= 25 February 2020 |quote= Official in charge of fight against the virus in western Daegu admits being member of cult after testing positive; 50 coworkers quarantined |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200225032613/https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3052129/coronavirus-infected-health-official-leading-south |archive-date= 25 February 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref name=\":750tested\"/> Within a few days, a petition to the nation's president urging for the disbandment of the church had over 750,000 signatures. Their headquarters in [[Gwacheon]] was raided by law enforcement and government officials said all 245,000 members of the religious group would be found and tested.<ref name=\":750tested\">{{cite web |url= https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-02-27/south-korea-coronavirus-cases-surveillance |title= Were you on this bus with a coronavirus patient? South Korea is on the hunt for infections |last= Kim |first= Victoria |date= 27 February 2020 |website= [[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=  |access-date= 28 February 2020 |quote= Even a public health official in charge of infection prevention in Seo-gu in Daegu was revealed to be a member of the church after he was diagnosed with the virus. Many members hide their affiliation with the controversial church. More than 750,000 signed a petition to the South Korean president urging that the church be disbanded. Authorities in Gyeonggi province raided the group\u2019s headquarters in the city of Gwacheon, alleging that the church had been slow to turn over its list of members. South Korean officials said they would track down and test all 245,000 members of the church. |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200227235952/https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-02-27/south-korea-coronavirus-cases-surveillance |archive-date= 27 February 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nOn 28 February, over 2,000 confirmed cases were reported.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030&act=view&list_no=366398&tag=&nPage=1 |title= The Updates of COVID-19 in Republic of Korea As of 28 February 2020 |author= <!--Not stated--> |date=  |website= [[Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] |publisher=  |access-date= 28 February 2020 |quote=  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200229165550/https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030&act=view&list_no=366398&tag=&nPage=1 |archive-date= 29 February 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n===March===\nOn 2 March, there were over 4,200 confirmed cases.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030&act=view&list_no=366416&tag=&nPage=1 |title= 476 additional cases are confirmed |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= [[Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] |publisher= |access-date= 2 March 2020 |quote= As of 0:00, 2 March 2020, 476 additional cases are confirmed, compared to yesterday afternoon (16:00, 1 March) which brings in total number of confirmed cases to 4,212.}}</ref> With an additional 4,000 cases of COVID-19 within two weeks, and roughly 60% of the total infections nationwide having stemmed from the church, the Seoul city government asked prosecutors to press charges against the religious group's founder and senior members for murder, causing harm, and for violating the Infectious Disease and Control Act.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://finance.yahoo.com/news/seoul-city-seeks-murder-charges-against-sect-founder-025259454.html |title= Seoul city seeks murder charges against sect founder over virus |author= <!--Not stated--> |date= 2 March 2020 |website= [[Yahoo!]] |publisher= [[Agence France-Presse]] |access-date= 4 March 2020 |quote=  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200302103858/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/seoul-city-seeks-murder-charges-against-sect-founder-025259454.html |archive-date= 2 March 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref> Interviews have occurred with all 230,000 members of the religious group and nearly 9,000 were said to be showing symptoms of the virus.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51695649 |title= Coronavirus: South Korea sect leader to face probe over deaths |author= <!--Not stated--> |date= 2 March 2020 |website= [[BBC]] |publisher=  |access-date= 4 March 2020 |quote=  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303014749/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51695649 |archive-date= 3 March 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref> Due to the number of infections in the country, ninety-five countries have banned or limited entry for South Korean passport holders.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/how-south-korea-lost-control-of-its-coronavirus-outbreak |title= How South Korea Lost Control of Its Coronavirus Outbreak |last= Kim |first= Suki |date= 4 March 2020 |website= [[The New Yorker]] |publisher=  |access-date= 5 March 2020 |quote= Citing the number of covid-19 diagnoses in South Korea, ninety-five countries, including China and Japan, now ban or limit entry by South Korean nationals. |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200305132902/https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/how-south-korea-lost-control-of-its-coronavirus-outbreak |archive-date= 5 March 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref> Testing is also conducted at drive-through testing sites where patients do not leave their vehicles, but are met by medical personnel in hazmat suits over several stations. The process is completed in a few minutes and results come in several days.<ref name=cnn20200302>{{cite web |url= https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/02/asia/coronavirus-drive-through-south-korea-hnk-intl/index.html |title= South Korea pioneers coronavirus drive-through testing station |last1= Watson |first1= Ivan |last2= Jeong |first2= Sophie |date= 3 March 2020 |website= [[CNN]] |publisher=  |access-date= 5 March 2020 |quote=  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200305011008/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/02/asia/coronavirus-drive-through-south-korea-hnk-intl/index.html |archive-date= 5 March 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref>\nOn 8 March, [[Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|KCDC]] in South Korea announced that 79.4% of confirmed COVID-19 cases were related to group infection. KCDC also announced that outbreak associated with [[Shincheonji Church of Jesus the Temple of the Tabernacle of the Testimony|Shincheonji Church]] totaled 4,482 infections, accounting for 62.8% of the total confirmed cases.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=ko:[\ucd9c\ucc98: \uc911\uc559\uc77c\ubcf4] [\ucf54\ub85c\ub098 \uc885\ud569] \uc11c\uc6b8\ubc31\ubcd1\uc6d0 \ud658\uc790 1\uba85 \ud655\uc9c4\u2026\"\ub300\uad6c \uac70\uc8fc \uc228\uae30\uace0 \ub0b4\uc6d0\" |url=https://news.joins.com/article/23724705 |work=[[JoongAng Ilbo]] |language=ko-kr}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.koreatimes.co.kr/pages/article.asp?newsIdx=285870|title=New cases of infections drop for third day|date=9 March 2020|website=m.koreatimes.co.kr|accessdate=11 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310190619/https://m.koreatimes.co.kr/pages/article.asp?newsIdx=285870|archive-date=10 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n13 March was the first time since the outbreak on 20 January in which the number of recoveries, 177, was larger than the number of those who newly tested positive, 110.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.mk.co.kr/news/it/view/2020/03/265693 |title= \ucf54\ub85c\ub098 '\uace8\ub4e0\ud06c\ub85c\uc2a4'\u2026\uc644\uce58>\uc2e0\uaddc \ud655\uc9c4\uc790 |author1= \uc11c\uc9c4\uc6b0 |author2= \uc774\uc11d\ud76c |author3= \uc6b0\uc131\ub355 |date= 13 March 2020 |website= \ub9e4\uc77c\uacbd\uc81c MBN |publisher=  |access-date= 17 March 2020 |quote=  |language= Korean |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319095345/https://www.mk.co.kr/news/it/view/2020/03/265693/ |archive-date= 19 March 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.donga.com/news/article/all/20200315/100164765/1 |title= \ub300\uad6c\uc11c \ucf54\ub85c\ub09819 \ud655\uc9c4\uc790 \ubcf4\ub2e4 \uc644\uce58\uc790 \ub9ce\uc740 '\uace8\ub4e0\ud06c\ub85c\uc2a4' \ud655\uc5f0 |author= <!--Not stated--> |date= 15 March 2020 |website= DongA |publisher=  |access-date= 17 March 2020 |quote=  |language= Korean |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200315182415/http://www.donga.com/news/article/all/20200315/100164765/1 |archive-date= 15 March 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.newdaily.co.kr/site/data/html/2020/03/15/2020031500028.html |title= 15\uc77c \uc6b0\ud55c\ucf54\ub85c\ub098 \ud655\uc9c4\uc790 8162\uba85\u2026'\uace8\ub4e0 \ud06c\ub85c\uc2a4' \uc0ac\ud758\uc9f8 |author= \uae40\ub3d9\uc6b0 |date= 15 March 2020 |website= New Daily |publisher=  |access-date= 17 March 2020 |quote=  |language= Korean |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319095344/http://www.newdaily.co.kr/site/data/html/2020/03/15/2020031500028.html |archive-date= 19 March 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref> <!--- This part is an analysis from South Korean media, please do not delete this section without any farther discussion on the talk page---> However, with the recent cluster of cases in the [[Seoul Capital Area]], there are new fears that infections may rise sharply.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/commentary/covid-19-coronavirus-south-korea-success-testing-tracking-model-12567158 |title=Commentary: South Korea has been exemplary. Even then, it hasn't slayed COVID-19 |access-date=24 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324084938/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/commentary/covid-19-coronavirus-south-korea-success-testing-tracking-model-12567158 |archive-date=24 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe controversy about Shincheonji also continued, and generated international interest. After the lawsuit started by the Mayor of Seoul, the police raided the church premises to check whether the list of members supplied by Shincheonji pursuant to a request by the authorities was, as the Mayor argued, not complete. The authorities checked the list seized during the raid with the one Shincheonji had supplied, and concluded that discrepancies were minor.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kim |first=So-hyun |date=17 March 2020 |title='Shincheonji didn't lie about membership figures' |url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200317000667 |work=The Korea Herald |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318185856/http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200317000667 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe [[United States Commission on International Religious Freedom]] (USCIRF) expressed concern that religious freedom rights of Shincheonji members may be violated in South Korea by \"exaggerating the church's role in the outbreak,\" and stated that, \"USCIRF has received reports of individuals encountering discrimination at work and spousal abuse because of their affiliation with the church.\"<ref name=\"USCIRF\">{{cite web |url=https://www.uscirf.gov/sites/default/files/2020%20Factsheet%20Covid-19%20and%20FoRB.pdf |title=The Global Response to the Coronavirus: Impact on Religious Practice and Religious Freedom |last=U.S. Commission on International Religious Freedom |date=March 2020|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> USCIRF reported that South Korean \"Vice Minister of Health Kim Kang-lip has publicly stated that the Shincheonji church has cooperated with authorities.\"<ref name=\"USCIRF\"/> The Belgian NGO [[Human Rights Without Frontiers]] and [[CESNUR]] released a \"White Paper\" claiming that, although it did make \"mistakes\" in its management of the crisis, Shincheonji had also been discriminated because of its status as an unpopular group in South Korea.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Human Rights without frontiers release white paper on Coronavirus |url=https://m.risingbd.com/english/national/news/68988/Human-Rights-without-frontiers-release-white-paper-on-Coronavirus |work=[[Risingbd.com]] |location=[[Dhaka]] |date=18 March 2020 |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319233319/https://m.risingbd.com/english/national/news/68988/Human-Rights-without-frontiers-release-white-paper-on-Coronavirus |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Mener kristen sekt er utsatt for jakt p\u00e5 syndebukk for koronautbruddet |url=https://www.vl.no/nyhet/mener-kristen-sekt-er-utsatt-for-jakt-pa-syndebukk-for-koronautbruddet-1.1691863?paywall=true |work=[[V\u00e5rt Land (Norwegian newspaper)|V\u00e5rt Land]] |location=Oslo |date=March 31, 2020 |access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, around 79 church devotees were infected with the virus after attending the [[River of Grace Community Church]]. The infections were claimed to have been caused by spraying salt-water into followers' mouths, under the belief that this would protect them from the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075421/coronavirus-salt-water-spray-infects-46-church-goers|title=Coronavirus: saltwater spray infects 46 church-goers in South Korea|date=16 March 2020|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318074249/https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075421/coronavirus-salt-water-spray-infects-46-church-goers|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/16/South-Korea-church-used-saltwater-spray-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/9881584365228/|title=South Korea church used saltwater spray amid coronavirus outbreak|website=UPI|language=en|access-date=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318074251/https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/16/South-Korea-church-used-saltwater-spray-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/9881584365228/|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Nearly 140 churches in Gyeonggi Province, which surrounds Seoul and is part of the [[Greater Seoul Area]], will be closed if they do not implement preventative measures, including temperature checks, two-meter separation, and the wearing of masks.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/east-asia/article/3075527/coronavirus-south-korea-threatens-close-churches-not-enforcing |title= Coronavirus: South Korea threatens to close churches for not enforcing preventive measures |author= <!--Not stated--> |date=17 March 2020 |website= [[South China Morning Post]] |publisher= Reuters and Associated Press |access-date= 31 March 2020 |quote= }}</ref> As more churches are holding services despite a government order for social distancing, on 30 March, the controversial Manmin Central Church in Guro, Seoul became a cluster with 22 infections linked to a gathering in early March in which the group was preparing stock footage to use for online worship services. Other church clusters have appears in the cities of Suwon, Busan, Geochang, and Bucheon.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3077497/coronavirus-cluster-emerges-another-south-korean |title= Coronavirus cluster emerges at another South Korean church, as others press ahead with Sunday services\n|author= Park Chan-kyong |date= 30 March 2020 |website= [[South China Morning Post]] |publisher= |access-date= 31 March 2020 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n===April \u2013 present outbreak===\nAs infection rates have risen outside Korea leading to increases of sick arriving in the country (476 of 9,661 cases were imported as of 30 March), the KCDC will be implanting stronger infectious disease control measures for travelers coming from overseas as of 1 April. Additionally, new self-quarantine measures for travelers coming from Europe or the United States will be in effect from the same day. For example, those showing symptoms but test negative, and those who are without symptoms and are staying short-term in Korea, need to quarantine for two weeks in a government provided facility.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030&act=view&list_no=366687&tag=&nPage=2 |title= The updates on COVID-19 in Korea as of 30 March |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 30 March 2020 |website= [[Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] |publisher= |access-date= 31 March 2020 |quote= }}</ref> Costs for the stay at the facility are the responsibility of the individual and total 100,000 won (US$81) per day.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2020/04/119_287412.html |title= Korea deports Taiwanese woman for refusing to stay at quarantine facility |author= Jung Min-ho |date= 6 April 2020 |website= The Korea Times |publisher= |access-date= 7 April 2020 |quote=  }}</ref> A few days later, a Taiwanese woman was deported on 5 April for refusing to stay in a quarantine facility as she initially agreed and then later disagreed with paying for the cost of staying at the government designated facility, reportedly costing around 100,000 won per day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200406004451315|title=(LEAD) Taiwanese woman deported for refusing to stay at quarantine facility|last=\uc774\ubbfc\uc9c0|date=2020-04-06|website=Yonhap News Agency|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n45 people are being investigated by the police for allegedly violating COVID-19 self-isolation. Under the revised anti-infectious disease law, violators can face up to a year in prison, a 10 million won fine, or in the case of foreign passport holders\u2014deportation.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2020/04/177_287168.html |title= Coronavirus: 45 under police investigation for breaking self-isolation rules |author= Park Si-soo |date= 1 April 2020 |website= The Korea Times |publisher= |access-date= 2 April 2020 |quote= }}</ref> \n\nSeeing the [[Misinformation related to the 2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic|infodemic]] on COVID-19 information starting in China and spreading to Korea and the US, fake news researcher [[Cha Meeyoung]] of [[KAIST]] and the [[Institute for Basic Science]], along with researchers from [[Ewha Womans University]], started the multilingual Facts Before Rumors campaign to separate common claims seen online.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ibs.re.kr/cop/bbs/BBSMSTR_000000000739/selectBoardArticle.do?nttId=18241 |title= \u201cFact before rumors\u201d campaign just began by the IBS Data Science Group |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 26 March 2020 |website= [[Institute for Basic Science]] |publisher= |access-date= 31 March 2020 |quote= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ibs.re.kr/cop/bbs/BBSMSTR_000000000971/selectBoardArticle.do?nttId=18234&pageIndex=1&searchCnd=&searchWrd= |title= \ucf54\ub85c\ub098\ubc14\uc774\ub7ec\uc2a4\uc640 \uc778\ud3ec\ub370\ubbf9 |author=[[Cha Meeyoung]] |date= 24 March 2020 |website= [[Institute for Basic Science]] |publisher= |access-date= 30 March 2020 |quote= |language= Korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://dongascience.donga.com/news.php?idx=35457 |title= \"\ub3d9\ub0a8\uc544\u00b7\ub0a8\ubbf8 \ucf54\ub85c\ub098 \uac00\uc9dc\ub274\uc2a4 \ub9c9\uace0 '\uc9c4\uc9dc\ub274\uc2a4' \uc804\ud558\uc790\" \uad6d\ub0b4 \uacfc\ud559\uc790 \ud314 \uac77\uc5b4 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 25 March 2020 |website= Donga Science |publisher= |access-date= 30 March 2020 |quote= |language= Korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.hankyung.com/opinion/article/2020032509531 |title= [\ucc28\ubbf8\uc601\uc758 \ub370\uc774\ud130\ub85c \ubcf8 \uc138\uc0c1] '\uc778\ud3ec\ub370\ubbf9'\uc758 \uc2dc\ub300 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 25 March 2020 |website= \ud55c\uad6d\uacbd\uc81c |publisher= |access-date= 30 March 2020 |quote= |language= Korean}}</ref>\n\nA Canadian cast member with the touring ''[[The Phantom of the Opera (1986 musical)|The Phantom of the Opera]]'' stage play entered Korea on March 12, participated for roughly two weeks, and tested positive 2 April. An American colleague tested positive on 4 April, which shut down production of the musical until 14 April while the venue could be disinfected and contacts of the staff, those staying in the same hotel, and over 8,000 people who recently attended were contacted by health authorities who told them to stay indoors and contact a testing center if they develop symptoms.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/art/2020/04/398_287384.html |title= Over 8,000 audience members to be monitored after musical actors test positive for COVID-19 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 5 April 2020 |website= The Korea Times |publisher= Yonhap News |access-date= 7 April 2020 |quote= More than 8,000 people who attended the musical \"Phantom of the Opera\" in Seoul will be closely monitored after two cast members tested positive for the novel coronavirus, authorities said Friday.}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/South Korea medical cases chart}}\n[[File:CoViD-19 KR.svg|thumb|right|upright=2|Number of cases (blue) and number of deaths (red) on a [[logarithmic scale]].]]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/South Korea medical cases}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==Containment==\nIn its efforts to fight and contain the virus, South Korea has combined testing with contact tracing.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nInfected South Koreans are required to go into isolation in government shelters. Their phones and credit card data are used to trace their prior movements and find their contacts. Those who are determined to have been near the infected individual receive phone alerts with information about their prior movements.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Virus Can Be Stopped, but Only With Harsh Steps, Experts Say|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/22/health/coronavirus-restrictions-us.html|website=The New York Times|date=23 March 2020|access-date=23 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324001725/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/22/health/coronavirus-restrictions-us.html|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Chun Byung-Chul, an epidemiologist at Korea University, high-risk patients who have underlying illnesses are prioritized for hospitalization. Patients with moderate symptoms are sent to \"repurposed corporate training facilities and spaces provided by public institutions,\" where they receive observation and medical support. Patients who recover and test negative twice are released. Close contacts and infected individuals with minimal symptoms who can measure their own temperatures and whose family members are free of any chronic disease are required to self-quarantine for two weeks. Local monitoring teams calls the quarantined twice a day to make sure that they stay where they are and to ask about symptoms.<ref>{{cite web|title=Coronavirus cases have dropped sharply in South Korea. What's the secret to its success?|url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/03/coronavirus-cases-have-dropped-sharply-south-korea-whats-secret-its-success|website=Science|date=17 March 2020|access-date=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320205413/https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/03/coronavirus-cases-have-dropped-sharply-south-korea-whats-secret-its-success|archive-date=20 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Preventive measures==\nThose ordered to self-quarantine are required to download an app that alerts officials if the patient moves outside of the quarantine. Violators are fined up to $2,500.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news |title=How South Korea Flattened the Curve |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/23/world/asia/coronavirus-south-korea-flatten-curve.html |website=The New York Times |date=23 March 2020 |access-date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323230039/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/23/world/asia/coronavirus-south-korea-flatten-curve.html |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Impacts and reactions ==\n[[File:20200322 \ucf54\ub85c\ub09819 \ud0c0\uc2dc\ub3c4 \ud655\uc9c4\uc790 \uc774\uc1a1(\ubd80\uc0b0\uc758\ub8cc\uc6d0) 05.jpg|thumb|[[Commons:Category:Transfer of a COVID-19 confirmed patient by Busan Medical Center using Busan Fire Services ambulance, 22 March 2020|Transfer of a COVID-19 confirmed patient by Busan Medical Center]]]]\n[[File:Coronavirus Check by Drive-Through.jpg|thumb|At the drive-through test center the medical staff examines patients with suspected [[COVID-19]] while in the vehicle. <br /> <br />The entire procedure of collecting a sample of secretions taking less than 10 minutes, and it's deployed to dozens of locations including [[Seoul]],[[Daegu]],[[Goyang]], [[Incheon]] and [[Sejong]].<ref name=\"businessinsider1\">{{cite web|author=Hyonhee Shin, Reuters |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/south-korea-launches-drive-thru-coronavirus-testing-facilities-as-demand-soars-2020-2?r=AU&IR=T |title=South Korea sets up drive-thru clinics to test for coronavirus |publisher=Business Insider |date= |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51836898 Coronavirus in South Korea: How 'trace, test and treat' may be saving lives] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312212652/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51836898 |date=12 March 2020 }}</ref> <br /> <br />*Banner: Coronavirus-19 drive-thru  screening clinic<ref>{{cite web|author=Dair\u00edn Frawley in Seoul |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/abroad/irishwoman-in-south-korea-drive-through-testing-for-coronavirus-no-human-contact-1.4197702 |title=Irishwoman in South Korea: Drive-through testing for coronavirus, no human contact |publisher=Irishtimes.com |date=2020-01-04 |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/09/asia/south-korea-coronavirus-intl-hnk/index.html South Korea has 'passed the peak' of the coronavirus outbreak, health minister hopes ] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310121826/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/09/asia/south-korea-coronavirus-intl-hnk/index.html |date=10 March 2020 }}</ref>]]\n[[File:COVID19 South Korea pharmacy with sold out sign.jpg|thumb|Sign in Daejeon pharmacy stating all masks are sold out]]\n[[File:COVID19 South Korea pharmacy long line.jpg|thumb|Line outside a pharmacy in Sejong City awaiting the store to open so they can buy masks]]\n\nAs of 18 March, South Korea's [[KOSPI]] stock index has dropped nearly 30% compared to a month ago. The drop precipitated on 23 February, when the country raised the coronavirus alert to 'highest level'.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Huang |first1=Eustance |title=South Korea stocks drop nearly 4% as country raises coronavirus alert to 'highest level' |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/24/asia-markets-south-korea-coronavirus-currencies-china.html |website=CNBC |language=en |date=23 February 2020 |access-date=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227131602/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/24/asia-markets-south-korea-coronavirus-currencies-china.html |archive-date=27 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> As of 15 March, the KOSPI closed at 1,771.44 and the Kosdaq finished at 524 points, down 7%, prompting the Financial Supervisory Commission to impose a six-month ban on short-selling, the first such drastic action in nearly nine years. This was despite a markedly lower daily increase in cases. Automaker [[Hyundai Motor Company]], having shut down its factories as the outbreak intensified, saw exports drop 21.4% in February from the same month last year.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kirk |first1=Donald |title=Coronavirus Hits South Korean Markets Despite Easing Of Crisis |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/donaldkirk/2020/03/15/coronavirus-hits-south-korean-markets-despite-easing-of-crisis/ |website=Forbes |language=en |date=15 March 2020 |access-date=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318151222/https://www.forbes.com/sites/donaldkirk/2020/03/15/coronavirus-hits-south-korean-markets-despite-easing-of-crisis/ |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Social impact ===\n[[File:20200311 \ud604\uc7a5\ubc29\ubb38 \ucf54\ub85c\ub09819 \uad00\ub828 \ucf54\ud638\ud2b8 \uaca9\ub9ac\ud574\uc81c \ubcd1\uc6d0 \ub4f1(\uc9c4\uad6c \ub4dc\ub77c\uc774\ube0c\uc2a4\ub8e8) 02.jpg|thumb|Drive-through test center in Busan]]\nAs of 25 February, Daegu officials were aggressively warning residents to take precautions, while allowing private businesses such as restaurants to stay open. As a precautionary measure, many restaurants check the temperatures of their customers before accepting them. It is common for \"offices, hotels, and other large buildings\" to use thermal image cameras in order to identify people with fevers.<ref name=\"auto\"/> All Daegu's public libraries, museums, churches, day-care centers and courts had been closed.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sang-Hun |first1=Choe |title=In Coronavirus Crisis, Korean City Tries Openness, a Contrast to China |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/25/world/asia/daegu-south-korea-coronavirus.html |website=The New York Times |date=25 February 2020 |access-date=13 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303064635/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/25/world/asia/daegu-south-korea-coronavirus.html |archive-date=3 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{Update inline|reason=What happened since then?|date=March 2020}}\n\nApart from the city of Daegu and the church community involved, most of South Korea is operating close to normality, although nine planned festivals have been closed and tax-free retailers are closing.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pharmaceutical-technology.com/features/coronavirus-affected-countries-south-korea-covid-19-outbreak-measures-impact/|title=South Korea Coronavirus: Outbreak, measures and impact|language=en-GB|access-date=23 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222033431/https://www.pharmaceutical-technology.com/features/coronavirus-affected-countries-south-korea-covid-19-outbreak-measures-impact/|archive-date=22 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The South Korean military manpower agency made an announcement that conscription from Daegu will temporarily be suspended.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.mt.co.kr/mtview.php?no=2020022313237612860|script-title=ko:\uc774\uc778\uc601 \"\uc804\uad6d \ud559\uad50 '\uac1c\ud559\uc5f0\uae30' \uac80\ud1a0\ud574\uc57c\"\u2026 \uad50\uc721\ub2f9\uad6d\uc5d0 \ub300\ucc45 \uc8fc\ubb38 \u2013 \uba38\ub2c8\ud22c\ub370\uc774 \ub274\uc2a4|date=23 February 2020|website=news.mt.co.kr|language=ko|access-date=23 February 2020|title=Archived copy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226102822/https://news.mt.co.kr/mtview.php?no=2020022313237612860|archive-date=26 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The ''Daegu Office of Education'' decided to postpone the start of every school in the region by one week.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200221006900325|title=Military to temporarily suspend drafting soldiers from Daegu|last=\ucd5c\uc218\ud5a5|date=21 February 2020|website=Yonhap News Agency|language=en|access-date=23 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223083157/https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200221006900325|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nNumerous educational institutes have temporarily shut down, including dozens of kindergartens in [[Daegu]] and several elementary schools in [[Seoul]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moe.go.kr/boardCnts/view.do?boardID=294&boardSeq=79822&lev=0&searchType=null&statusYN=W&page=1&s=moe&m=020402&opType=N|title= Korean Ministry of Education|last=|first=|date=|website=Ministry of Education (South Korea)|access-date=24 February 2020}}</ref> As of 18 February, most universities in South Korea had announced plans to postpone the start of the spring semester. This included 155 universities planning to delay the semester start by two weeks to 16 March, and 22 universities planning to delay the semester start by one week to 9 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.unn.net/news/articleView.html?idxno=226388|script-title=ko:177\uac1c \ub300\ud559 \uac1c\uac15 \uc5f0\uae30\u00b7\u00b7\u00b780%\uac00 '2\uc8fc \uacb0\uc815'|date=18 February 2020|website=\ud55c\uad6d\ub300\ud559\uc2e0\ubb38|language=ko|access-date=23 February 2020|title=Archived copy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226102832/http://news.unn.net/news/articleView.html?idxno=226388|archive-date=26 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Also, on 23 February 2020, all kindergartens, elementary schools, middle schools, and high schools were announced to delay the semester start from 2 to 9 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.donga.com/news/article/all/20200223/99835113/2|script-title=ko:\uad50\uc721\ubd80 \"\uc804\uad6d \uc720\u00b7\ucd08\u00b7\uc911\u00b7\uace0 1\uc8fc\uc77c \uac1c\ud559 \uc5f0\uae30\u20263\uc6d49\uc77c \uac1c\ud559\"|date=23 February 2020|website=donga.com|language=ko|access-date=24 February 2020|title=Archived copy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223204454/http://www.donga.com/news/article/all/20200223/99835113/2|archive-date=23 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>{{Update inline|reason=Did they end up postponing? Was the duration extended?|date=March 2020}}\n\nThe economy of South Korea is forecast to grow 1.9%, which is down from 2.1%. The government has provided 136.7 billion [[South Korean won|won]] for local governments as support.<ref name=\":4\" /> The government has also organized the procurement of masks and other hygiene equipment.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nEntertainment agency [[SM Entertainment]] reportedly donated five hundred million [[South Korean won|won]] in efforts to fight the disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailian.co.kr/news/view/871813?sc=Naver|script-title=ko:SM\uc5d4\ud130\ud14c\uc778\uba3c\ud2b8, \ucf54\ub85c\ub09819 \ud655\uc0b0 \ubc29\uc9c0 \uc704\ud55c \uc131\uae08 5\uc5b5\uc6d0 \uae30\ubd80|publisher=Dailian|date=28 February 2020|title=Archived copy|access-date=28 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228032331/https://www.dailian.co.kr/news/view/871813%3Fsc%3DNaver|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xportsnews.com/?ac=article_view&entry_id=1241496 |script-title=ko:SM, \ucf54\ub85c\ub098 19 \uc0ac\ud0dc\uc5d0 5\uc5b5\uc6d0 \uae30\ubd80 \"\uc758\ub8cc\uc9c4 \uc704\ud574 \ud798 \uc368\ub2ec\ub77c\" [\uacf5\uc2dd\uc785\uc7a5]|publisher=X Sports News|date=28 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvreport.co.kr/2034049|script-title=ko:SM\uc5d4\ud130, \ucf54\ub85c\ub09819 \uc0ac\ud0dc 5\uc5b5 \uae30\ubd80\u2026\"\uc758\ub8cc\uc9c4\uc5d0 \ud798\ub418\uace0\uc790\" [\uacf5\uc2dd]|publisher=TV Report|date=28 February 2020|title=Archived copy|access-date=28 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228032333/https://www.tvreport.co.kr/2034049|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[K-pop|K-POP]] industry, the rapid spread of the coronavirus within South Korea has led to the cancellations or postponing of concerts and other events for K-POP acts within and outside of South Korea, with example situations including the cancellation of the remaining Asia dates and the Europe leg for [[Seventeen (South Korean band)|Seventeen]]\u2019s Ode To You Tour on 9 February 2020 and the cancellation of all Seoul dates for [[BTS (band)|BTS]]' [[Map of the Soul Tour]].<ref>{{cite tweet|user=pledis_17|number=1226355059794952193|date=9 February 2020 |script-title=ko:SEVENTEEN WORLD TOUR [ODE TO YOU] \ucde8\uc18c \uad00\ub828 \uacf5\uc9c0}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=bts_bighit|number=1233195543842549760|date=28 February 2020|script-title=ko:[\uacf5\uc9c0] #BTS MAP OF THE SOUL TOUR \u2013 SEOUL \uacf5\uc5f0 \ucde8\uc18c \uc548\ub0b4 (+ENG/JPN/CHN)}}</ref>\n\n===Travel restrictions===\n{{See|Travel restrictions related to the 2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:Map of Travel restrictions related to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic - korea.svg|thumb|500px|\n{{legend|#55D400|South Korea}}\n{{legend|#AA0000|Entrance refused to people from South Korea}}\n{{legend|#FF5555|Entrance refused to people from some areas of South korea}}\n{{legend|#003380|Imposed quarantine on people arriving from South Korea}}\n{{legend|#9dc4ff|Other restrictions (self-quarantines, medical examination requirements, monitoring measures)}}]]\nAs of 20 March, a total of 171 countries and territories had issued entry bans or suspended visas for travelers from South Korea.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u9751\uc774 '\ud0a4\ud2b8 \uc218\ucd9c \uc790\ub791' UAE\ub3c4 \uc5b4\uc81c \ube57\uc7a5\u2026 171\uad6d\uc774 \ud55c\uad6d\u767c \uc785\uad6d\uae08\uc9c0|date=20 March 2020|publisher=Chosun.com|url=http://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2020/03/20/2020032000121.html|access-date=19 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319232044/http://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2020/03/20/2020032000121.html|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 16 March, USFK announced that travel restrictions for Cheonan city had been removed due to a decline in COVID-19 cases. Troops and Defense Department personnel residing in Cheonan were told to \"contact their command prior to returning to work.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=USFK COVID-19 Information|date=16 March 2020|publisher=usfk.mil|url=https://www.usfk.mil/Media/News/Article/2070556/usfk-covid-19-information/|access-date=23 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228025801/https://www.usfk.mil/Media/News/Article/2070556/usfk-covid-19-information/|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Government reactions ===\n[[File:20200227 \ucf54\ub85c\ub09819 \ub300\uc751 \uc911\uc559\uc7ac\ub09c\uc548\uc804\ub300\ucc45\ubcf8\ubd80 \ud68c\uc758(\uc7ac\ub09c\uc548\uc804\ub300\ucc45\ubcf8\ubd80) 01.jpg|thumb|Videotelephony of Central Disaster and Safety Countermeasure Headquarters]]\n\n===Number of inspections===\nThe Blue House announced on 28 February the current status of coronavirus tests in Korea, comparing the testing situation in the United States and Japan. The number of inspections was 26 and 120 times higher than in those countries respectively as of 28 Feb. The cumulative number of inspections was about 53,000 by South Korea, while Japan was about 2,000, and in US about 440 cases were examined.<ref name=chosun-numberoftests />\n\n===Reactions from KMA===\nOn 26 January, the Korean Medical Association (KMA) asked the government to temporarily bar entry to all travelers arriving from mainland China, but this recommendation was not followed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/how-south-korea-lost-control-of-its-coronavirus-outbreak|title=How South Korea Lost Control of Its Coronavirus Outbreak|first=Suki|last=Kim|website=The New Yorker|access-date=5 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305132902/https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/how-south-korea-lost-control-of-its-coronavirus-outbreak|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On 27 January, KMA President Choi Dae-zip said: \"The third confirmed case indicates that we have reached the point where we have to get rid of passive stance and actively prepare for the worsening of the situation, (and) the government should thoroughly monitor the trend of China's national outbreak of the virus and prepare administrative measures such as complete entry ban from China in case of the worst situation.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreabiomed.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=7284|title=[2019-Novel Coronavirus] Doctors join general public calling for entry ban on Chinese - Korea Biomedical Review|date=27 January 2020|website=www.koreabiomed.com}}</ref> On 3 February, The KMA recommended halting all travel from China, rather than only from Hubei province.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://world.kbs.co.kr/service/news_view.htm?lang=e&Seq_Code=151059|title=KMA Urges Expanding Restriction Measures to All of China|website=world.kbs.co.kr|access-date=24 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200212225559/http://world.kbs.co.kr/service/news_view.htm?lang=e&Seq_Code=151059|archive-date=12 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> After all, The KMA called for stronger government response in a total of six statements between 20 January, when the nation's first confirmed case occurred, and 18 February. A short time after that, cases spiked in Daegu and throughout the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2020/02/public-anger-swells-in-south-korea-over-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Public Anger Swells in South Korea Over Coronavirus Outbreak|first=Tae-jun|last=Kang|website=thediplomat.com|access-date=20 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229141909/https://thediplomat.com/2020/02/public-anger-swells-in-south-korea-over-coronavirus-outbreak/|archive-date=29 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Public reactions ===\n==== Presidential approval rating ====\nAlthough there are many confirmed cases of COVID-19, President [[Moon Jae-in]]'s approval rating rose by two percentage points to 44%. During the MERS crisis, the previous President [[Park Geun-hye]]'s approval rating had fallen sharply to 29% due to inadequate management the MERS infection.<ref>{{cite news|trans-title=At the time of MERS, Park Geun-hye support rate plunged\u2026 Corona 19 Moon Jae-in support rate rather rises |script-title=ko:\uba54\ub974\uc2a4 \ub550 \u6734 \uc9c0\uc9c0\uc728 \ud3ed\ub77d\u2026\ucf54\ub85c\ub09819\uc5d4 \u6587 \uc9c0\uc9c0\uc728 \uc624\ud788\ub824 \uc0c1\uc2b9 |url=https://www.hankyung.com/politics/article/2020030620737 |work=[[Korea Economic Daily]] |language=ko-kr}}</ref>\n\nIn opinion poll conducted by Gallup Korea in the second week of March 2020, president Moon's approval rating has risen by 5% to 49%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gallup.co.kr/dir/GallupKoreaDaily/GallupKoreaDailyOpinion_392(20200313).pdf|title=\ub370\uc77c\ub9ac \uc624\ud53c\ub2c8\uc5b8 \uc81c392\ud638(2020\ub144 3\uc6d4 2\uc8fc) - \ucd1d\uc120 \uae30\ub300, \ucc28\uae30 \uc815\uce58 \uc9c0\ub3c4\uc790, \ucf54\ub85c\ub09819, \ub9c8\uc2a4\ud06c \uad00\ub828 \uc778\uc2dd|work=\ud55c\uad6d\uac24\ub7fd|date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Anti-foreigner sentiment ====\nIn February 2020, an entrance to a South Korean restaurant in downtown [[Seoul]] reportedly had a sign in red Chinese characters stating: \"No Chinese Allowed.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/no-chinese-allowed-racism-and-fear-are-now-spreading-along-with-the-coronavirus-2020-01-29|title='No Chinese allowed': Racism and fear are now spreading along with the coronavirus|last=Fottrell|first=Quentin|website=MarketWatch |access-date=2 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202231235/https://www.marketwatch.com/story/no-chinese-allowed-racism-and-fear-are-now-spreading-along-with-the-coronavirus-2020-01-29|archive-date=2 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \"No Chinese\" signs have been cropping up, and some businesses are simply banning all foreigners.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/02/coronavirus-brings-anti-chinese-sentiment-south-korea-200221094732254.html|title=Coronavirus brings out anti-Chinese sentiment in South Korea|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312151251/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/02/coronavirus-brings-anti-chinese-sentiment-south-korea-200221094732254.html|archive-date=12 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Some foreign residents have been excluded from the government mask distribution program as it is currently only allowed to 1.25 million foreigners who were subscribed to the public health insurance.<ref>[http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200314000082 [Exclusive] Expats sidelined in Seoul\u2019s mask-rationing {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314123806/http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200314000082 |date=14 March 2020 }}</ref> Concerning COVID-19, more than 760,000 South Korean citizens have signed a petition lobbying the government to ban Chinese tourists from entering the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=Not Enough Doctors in Daegu: As Virus Cases Rise, South Korea's Response Is Criticized |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/not-enough-doctors-in-daegu-as-virus-cases-rise-south-koreas-response-is-criticized-11582547600 |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=24 February 2020 |access-date=29 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229101452/https://www.wsj.com/articles/not-enough-doctors-in-daegu-as-virus-cases-rise-south-koreas-response-is-criticized-11582547600 |archive-date=29 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Shin28Jan2020\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-reaction-southkorea-idUSKBN1ZR0QJ|title=South Koreans call in petition for Chinese to be barred over virus|last=Shin|first=Hyonhee|date=28 January 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=3 February 2020|url-status=live|last2=Cha|first2=Sangmi |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131154836/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-reaction-southkorea-idUSKBN1ZR0QJ|archive-date=31 January 2020}}</ref> The Daegu Lantern Festival mistakenly posted a notice in English that no foreigners are allowed to visit. However, the wrong sentence was removed and it was revealed a translation error by the PR agency regarding statement from a Daegu government official. The official in the Daegu city stated that the original message was the notification to foreign tourists about the delayed schedule of festival over COVID-19 concerns.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2020/03/177_285607.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=10 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305161517/http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2020/03/177_285607.html |archive-date=5 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Jamaicans have reported widespread discrimination,<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/article/news/20200328/jamaican-feels-ostracised-south-korea-over-covid-19 |title=Jamaican feels ostracised in South Korea over COVID-19 &#124; News |publisher=Jamaica Gleaner |date=2020-03-28 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> and foreigners were excluded from city wide stimulus funds, with the exception of Ansan city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200405000177 |title=Foreign residents shut out of virus relief funds |publisher=Koreaherald.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n=== International response ===\nOn 24 February, the United States [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC)]] upgraded the status of South Korea to level 3 (avoid non-essential travels due to widespread community transmission).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/notices/warning/coronavirus-south-korea|title=Coronavirus in South Korea \u2013 Warning \u2013 Level 3, Avoid Nonessential Travel \u2013 Travel Health Notices {{!}} Travelers' Health {{!}} CDC|website=wwwnc.cdc.gov|access-date=29 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225051122/https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/notices/warning/coronavirus-south-korea|archive-date=25 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 February, [[Charles Schwab Corporation]] advised employees who had travelled to China and South Korea to self-quarantine for 14 days.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-charles-schwab-idUSKCN20M2VS|title=Schwab tells employees to self-quarantine after visiting China, South Korea|date=28 February 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=29 February 2020|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229023846/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-charles-schwab-idUSKCN20M2VS|archive-date=29 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Multiple companies such as [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]], [[Google]], [[Toronto-Dominion Bank|TD Bank Group]], [[Bank of Nova Scotia]], [[London Stock Exchange Group]], and [[Cargill|Cargill, Inc.]] deferred all non-essential travels to areas affected by the outbreak.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-amazon-com-idUSKCN20M2TZ|title=Amazon defers 'non-essential' moves even in U.S. as corporate travel bans spread|date=28 February 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=29 February 2020|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228222152/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-amazon-com-idUSKCN20M2TZ|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAs of 8 March, [[United States Forces Korea|US military]] has suspended all travels to and from South Korea for all military personnel and their family over the concern of the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/health/coronavirus-us-army-south-korea-suspends-travel-soldiers|title=US Army suspends travel for soldiers, families to and from South Korea amid coronavirus outbreak|last=Wallace|first=Danielle|date=8 March 2020|website=Fox News|language=en-US|access-date=8 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308133810/https://www.foxnews.com/health/coronavirus-us-army-south-korea-suspends-travel-soldiers|archive-date=8 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAs of 10 March, 109 countries or regions restrict entry of visitors from South Korea.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u97d3 \uc785\uad6d \uc81c\ud55c 109\uacf3\u2026\uc774\ud0c8\ub9ac\uc544 \uc2dc\uc791\ud55c \uad6d\uac00\ubd09\uc1c4, \uc720\ub7fd \ubc88\uc9c0\ub098|date=10 March 2020 |publisher=JoongAng Ilbo|url=https://news.joins.com/article/23726399}}</ref>\n\n=== View of foreign media on COVID-19 in Korea ===\n''[[The Washington Post]]'' has praised the South Korean government's handling of coronavirus outbreak and stated that South Korea is a model for the U.S. response instead of Iran.<ref>{{cite web|author=Paige Winfield Cunningham|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/paloma/the-health-202/2020/03/13/the-health-202-why-south-korea-not-iran-is-a-model-for-u-s-coronavirus-response/5e6a58be88e0fa101a747d62/|title=The Health 202:Why-South Korea not Iran is a model for U.S. coronavirus response|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=13 March 2020|access-date=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314074409/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/paloma/the-health-202/2020/03/13/the-health-202-why-south-korea-not-iran-is-a-model-for-u-s-coronavirus-response/5e6a58be88e0fa101a747d62/|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> ''The Washington Post'' also appreciated South Korea's response as a successful model for democratic countries.<ref>{{cite web|first=Josh|last=Rogin|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/11/south-korea-shows-that-democracies-can-succeed-against-coronavirus/|title=South Korea shows that democracies can succeed against the coronavirus|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=11 March 2020|access-date=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314081252/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/03/11/south-korea-shows-that-democracies-can-succeed-against-coronavirus/|archive-date=14 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Agence France-Presse]] has compared South Korea's handling of coronavirus outbreak with China. The newspaper stated that \"While China locked down cities, Seoul embraced widespread testing and public notice of movements of those infected, raising some privacy concerns\". Also, AFP analyzed that the South Korean government handled the crisis using a model of open information, public participation, and widespread testing.<ref>{{cite web|author=AFP|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/can-south-korea-be-a-model-for-virus-hit-countries/|title=Can South Korea be a model for virus-hit countries?|work=[[The Times of Israel]]|date=12 March 2020|access-date=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316170319/https://www.timesofisrael.com/can-south-korea-be-a-model-for-virus-hit-countries/|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Additionally, according to the paper, Masahiro Kami, a chairperson of the Tokyo-based Medical Governance Research Institute stated that South Korea is a good model for every country for handling the coronavirus outbreak.<ref>{{cite web|author=AFP|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/can-south-korea-be-a-model-for-virus-hit-countries/|title=Can South Korea be a model for virus-hit countries?|quote=Japan \u2014 where nearly 600 people have been infected, with 12 deaths \u2014 has not undertaken widespread testing and could learn from South Korea\u2019s response, said Masahiro Kami, head of the Tokyo-based Medical Governance Research Institute.\"Testing is a crucial initial step to control the virus,\" Kami said, adding: \"It\u2019s a good model for every country.\"|work=[[The Times of Israel]]|date=12 March 2020|access-date=14 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316170319/https://www.timesofisrael.com/can-south-korea-be-a-model-for-virus-hit-countries/|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[WSJ]] analyzed the aggressive Coronavirus Test Program in South Korea. The government contacted the citizens proactively to test the coronavirus in various ways including a home visit, a quick 10 minutes drop off drive-through COVID-19 testing center free of charge. Although South Korea not yet defeated the outbreak, experts credit the emphasis on energetic COVID-19 test program with reducing case numbers and fatalities.<ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-south-korea-put-into-place-the-worlds-most-aggressive-coronavirus-testing-11584377217 How South Korea Put Into Place the World\u2019s Most Aggressive Coronavirus Test Program]{{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317074816/https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-south-korea-put-into-place-the-worlds-most-aggressive-coronavirus-testing-11584377217 |date=17 March 2020 }}</ref><ref>[https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/03/13/815441078/south-koreas-drive-through-testing-for-coronavirus-is-fast-and-free South Korea's Drive-Through Testing For Coronavirus Is Fast \u2014 And Free] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317032153/https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/03/13/815441078/south-koreas-drive-through-testing-for-coronavirus-is-fast-and-free |date=17 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n[[UPI]] has analyzed that South Korea's model has worked on handling coronavirus outbreak without any further harder restrictions on foreigners.<ref>{{cite web|author=Thomas Maresca|url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/13/Lessons-for-the-world-How-South-Korea-is-tackling-coronavirus/4601584109467/|title=Lessons for the world: How South Korea is tackling coronavirus|quote=However, the South Korean model seems to have worked to curtail a rapid outbreak originally tied to a secretive religious sect while avoiding the heavy-handed lockdown of an authoritarian regime such as China.|work=[[UPI]]|date=13 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316213420/https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/13/Lessons-for-the-world-How-South-Korea-is-tackling-coronavirus/4601584109467/|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The paper also observed that Health authorities have aggressively promoted hygiene and social distancing.<ref>{{cite web|author=Thomas Maresca|url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/13/Lessons-for-the-world-How-South-Korea-is-tackling-coronavirus/4601584109467/|title=Lessons for the world: How South Korea is tackling coronavirus|quote=Health authorities have aggressively promoted hygiene and social distancing through widespread public information campaigns, while mass disinfections are being conducted regularly in high-traffic locations such as subway and train stations.|work=[[UPI]]|date=13 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316213420/https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/13/Lessons-for-the-world-How-South-Korea-is-tackling-coronavirus/4601584109467/|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Additionally, according to the paper Kim Jong-hwan, an administrator at Seoul Metropolitan Eunpyeong Hospital positively evaluated the government's deal with coronavirus outbreak by stating that \"The government's response has been so well-organized. I'm proud of it.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Thomas Maresca|url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/13/Lessons-for-the-world-How-South-Korea-is-tackling-coronavirus/4601584109467/|title=Lessons for the world: How South Korea is tackling coronavirus|quote=\"The government's response has been so well-organized,\" Kim said. \"I'm proud of it.\"|work=[[UPI]]|date=13 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316213420/https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/13/Lessons-for-the-world-How-South-Korea-is-tackling-coronavirus/4601584109467/|archive-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine and [[BBC News]] concluded that the reason for the high number of confirmed cases of the coronavirus in South Korea is thanks to the relative \"openness\" and \"transparency\" in the Korean society.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Borowiec |first1=Steven |title=How South Korea's Coronavirus Outbreak Got so Quickly out of Control |url=https://time.com/5789596/south-korea-coronavirus-outbreak/ |website=Time |language=en |date=24 February 2020 |access-date=7 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305011745/https://time.com/5789596/south-korea-coronavirus-outbreak/ |archive-date=5 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> As for the rapid spread of the virus, the reason was the religious group [[Shincheonji Church of Jesus the Temple of the Tabernacle of the Testimony|Shincheonji Church]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51609840|title=Why did virus infections skyrocket in South Korea?|date=25 February 2020|accessdate=8 March 2020|website=bbc.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302191755/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51609840|archive-date=2 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[The Blue House]] announced on 28 February the current status of coronavirus tests in three countries: Korea, the United States, and Japan, and analyzed statistically the reasons why there were so many confirmed cases in South Korea: the number of inspections was 26 or 120 times higher than other countries. The cumulative number of inspections was about 53,000 in South Korea, with only 2,000 in Japan and 440 cases examined in the United States. After the tests, the rate of confirmed cases was highest in Japan (9.04%), followed by Korea (3.3%) and the United States (3.15%).<ref name=chosun-numberoftests>{{cite news |trans-title=The number of corona tests in Korea is 26 times that of Japan-this could be the reason for many reasons for the confirmed cases |script-title=ko:\u9751 \"\ud55c\uad6d, \ucf54\ub85c\ub098 \uac80\uc0ac \uc218 \uc77c\ubcf8\uc758 26\ubc30\"\u2026 \ud655\uc9c4\uc790 \ub9ce\uc740 \uc774\uc720 \ud574\uba85? \ucd9c\ucc98 |url=http://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2020/02/28/2020022803425.html |work=[[Chosun Ilbo]] |date=8 February 2020 |language=ko-kr |access-date=7 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301033030/https://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2020/02/28/2020022803425.html |archive-date=1 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[Bloomberg L.P.]] analyzed the reason for the low death rate in South Korea. South Korea experienced serious difficulties during the [[2015 Middle East respiratory syndrome outbreak in South Korea|outbreak of MERS]] in 2015 due to a lack of test kits. Afterwards, the country approved rapid deployment of COVID-19 test kits, and now they are able to test more than 10,000 people a day. In neighboring Japan, only about 2,700 people in total have been tested for COVID-19 as of 3 March. Officials in [[Seoul]] operate \"drive-thru\" testing stations for quick testing. Diagnostics company Seegene Inc. is also exporting its test kits to other countries including China, Europe and the US.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-04/south-korea-tests-hundreds-of-thousands-to-fight-virus-outbreak Virus Testing Blitz Appears to Keep Korea Death Rate Low] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309094739/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-04/south-korea-tests-hundreds-of-thousands-to-fight-virus-outbreak |date=9 March 2020 }}</ref><ref>[https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/seegene-launches-kfda-approved-covid-19-assay-301005858.html Seegene launches KFDA Approved COVID-19 Assay]{{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219191708/https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/seegene-launches-kfda-approved-covid-19-assay-301005858.html |date=19 February 2020 }}</ref>\n\n[[Agence France-Presse|AFP]] attributed the factors behind the low death rate of South Korea to the rigorous testing and the infected population profile. South Korea's widespread testing leads mild or asymptomatic cases to be identified so the proportion of dying goes down. Moreover, the infected population in the South Korea has a unique profile. Most of the country's infections are linked to the [[Shincheonji Church of Jesus]] and most of its members are young women. Statistics show that the virus is most deadly among older generations and men. So the death rate in South Korea is lower than other countries.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Can South Korea be a model for virus-hit countries? |date=11 March 2020 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/coronavirus-can-south-korea-be-a-model-for-virus-hit-countries |work=AFP |publisher=The Straits Times |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313052634/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/coronavirus-can-south-korea-be-a-model-for-virus-hit-countries |archive-date=13 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[CNN]] reported the innovative drive-through testing for COVID-19 in the northern city of [[Goyang]], which was inspired by the drive-through counters at [[Starbucks]].<ref name=cnn20200302/> [[Reuters]] detailed the new testing facilities in South Korea. Several drive-through coronavirus screening centres were built, including roadside testing facilities. Their purpose is to diagnose patients quickly, while preventing the infection of others in, e.g., a hospital waiting room or a community health center. The entire testing procedure takes several minutes.<ref name=\"businessinsider1\"/>\nWilliam Schaffner, a professor of preventive medicine and infectious diseases at Vanderbilt University School of Medicine, stressed the importance of the broad testing efforts in South Korea. It would provide us with an unclouded picture of the COVID-19 illness.<ref>[https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3065187/coronavirus-south-koreas-aggressive-testing-gives Coronavirus: South Korea\u2019s aggressive testing gives clues to true fatality rate] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310082405/https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3065187/coronavirus-south-koreas-aggressive-testing-gives |date=10 March 2020 }}</ref> [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]\u2019s Chief Health Officer, Brett Sutton has recommended the drive-thru coronavirus testing in Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.racgp.org.au/newsgp/clinical/drive-thru-coronavirus-testing-now-a-reality-in-so |title=Drive-thru coronavirus testing \u2018needs to be explored\u2019: Victorian health chief |publisher=RACGP |date= |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref> On 10 March, Australia opened the first drive-through testing station in [[Adelaide]].<ref name=\"abc.net.au\">[https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-10/australias-first-coronavirus-road-testing-station-opens-adelaide/12041978 First 'drive-thru' coronavirus testing station opens in South Australia] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310081432/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-10/australias-first-coronavirus-road-testing-station-opens-adelaide/12041978 |date=10 March 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"abc.net.au\"/>\n\n''[[Business Insider]]'' analyzed the difference of coverage of patient testing patients for COVID-19, comparing the USA to South Korea. Per million citizens, South Korea tested 700 times more than the USA.<ref name=fp20200227/> ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' explained South Korea's efforts of setting up several \"drive-thru\" coronavirus screening facilities as contributing to testing thousands of samples a day.<ref>[https://fortune.com/2020/03/03/coronavirus-us-test/ Other countries are testing patients for coronavirus by the tens of thousands. Why the U.S. is so far behind] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304213846/https://fortune.com/2020/03/03/coronavirus-us-test/ |date=4 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n[[CNN]] had an interview with South Korea health minister [[Park Neung-hoo]]. Park expressed cautiously his desire that the coronavirus outbreak is 'passed the peak' as per the result regarding the number of new daily infections has declined in recent days.<ref name=\"CNN-12\"/> The S. Korean government has the ability operate about 15,000 diagnostic test per day and has conducted over 190,000 tests by 10 March nationwide. Park also answered the inquiry from CNN about practicable tips for controlling COVID-19. Park believes that dealing with outbreaks by focusing efforts on early testing and global cooperation would be crucial instead of the lockdown option, as the virus could still spread quickly without testing.<ref name=\"CNN-12\"/> S. Korean authorities have arranged the two types of facilities, one for about 10% of coronavirus patients who required hospitalization and another for the patients who were only suffering from mild symptoms.<ref name=\"CNN-12\">CNN NEWS- 10 March 2020:[https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/09/asia/south-korea-coronavirus-intl-hnk/index.html South Korea has 'passed the peak' of the coronavirus outbreak, health minister hopes] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310121826/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/09/asia/south-korea-coronavirus-intl-hnk/index.html |date=10 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Coronavirus disease]]s, a group of closely related syndromes\n* [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in Asia]]\n\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|South Korea|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{notelist}}\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://mask.arrangy.com Mask Dashboard, real-time public surgical mask inventory information of nationwide and municipalities in Korea]\n{{commons category-inline}}<br>\n{{commons category-inline|Press releases about the COVID-19 pandemic in foreign languages by Ministry of Health and Welfare (South Korea)|Press releases about the COVID-19 pandemic by Ministry of Health and Welfare (South Korea)}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea| ]]\n[[Category:2020 in South Korea|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:History of Daegu]]\n[[Category:Christianity-related controversies]]\n[[Category:Christianity and medicine]]\n", "name_user": "CRau080", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eView of foreign media on COVID-19 in Korea:Some minor edits in par. on CNN interview with Health Minister Park.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_South_Korea"}
{"title_page": "Warren County, Illinois", "text_new": "{{Short description|County in Illinois}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox U.S. county|\n county  = Warren County|\n state = Illinois |\n seal = |\n founded = 1825|\n seat wl= Monmouth |\n largest city wl = Monmouth|\n area_total_sq_mi = 543 |\n area_land_sq_mi = 542 |\n area_water_sq_mi = 0.6 |\n area percentage = 0.1 |\n population_as_of = 2010|\n population_total = 17707 |\n pop_est_as_of = 2018 |\n population_est = 17032 |\n population_density_sq_mi = auto |\n web = www.warrencountyil.com|\n ex image = Warren County Courthouse in Monmouth.jpg|\n ex image cap = [[Warren County Courthouse (Illinois)|Warren County Courthouse]] in Monmouth\n| district = 17th\n| time zone = Central\n| named for= [[Joseph Warren]]\n}}\n\n'''Warren County''' is a [[County (United States)|county]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Illinois]]. According to the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]], it had a population of 17,707.<ref name=\"QF\">{{cite web|title=State & County QuickFacts|url=http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/17/17187.html|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=July 9, 2014}}</ref> Its [[county seat]] is [[Monmouth, Illinois|Monmouth]].<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx|accessdate=2011-06-07|title=Find a County|publisher=National Association of Counties}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nWarren County was organized in 1825 out of [[Pike County, Illinois|Pike County]] which consisted of all portions of the state north and west of the Illinois River before 1825. [[Henderson County, Illinois|Henderson County]] was formed in 1841 from the western area of Warren County.\n\nWarren County was named for Dr. [[Joseph Warren]], killed at the [[Battle of Bunker Hill]] in 1775. He is believed to have been the first officer to die in the [[American Revolutionary War|Revolutionary War]].\n\nThe current courthouse, constructed of red Portage stone, was completed in 1895.\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Warren County Illinois 1825.png|Warren County from the time of its creation to 1831\nFile:Warren County Illinois 1831.png|Between 1831 and 1835, Mercer County was temporarily attached to Warren until it could organize its own county government.<ref>White, Jesse. ''[http://www.cyberdriveillinois.com/publications/pdf_publications/ipub15.pdf Origin and Evolution of Illinois Counties]''. State of Illinois, March 2010.</ref>\nFile:Warren_County,_Illinois_-_1835.png|Warren County between 1835 and 1841\nFile:Warren County Illinois 1841.png|Warren County in 1841, reduced to its current borders by the creation of Henderson County\n</gallery>\n\n==Geography==\nAccording to the [[U.S. Census Bureau]], the county has a total area of {{convert|543|sqmi}}, of which {{convert|542|sqmi}} is land and {{convert|0.6|sqmi}} (0.1%) is water.<ref name=\"census-density\"/>\n\n===Climate and weather===\n{{climate chart\n|[[Monmouth, Illinois]]\n|15|31|1.62\n|21|37|1.72\n|30|49|2.85\n|41|63|3.76\n|51|73|4.27\n|60|81|4.26\n|64|85|4.33\n|62|83|4.02\n|54|77|3.45\n|43|65|2.97\n|32|49|2.74\n|20|35|2.32\n|float=right\n|units=imperial\n|clear=both\n|source=The Weather Channel<ref name=\"weather\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.weather.com/weather/wxclimatology/monthly/graph/USIL0791\n  |title=Monthly Averages for Monmouth, Illinois\n  |accessdate=2011-01-27\n  |publisher=The Weather Channel\n}}</ref>}}\nIn recent years, average temperatures in the county seat of Monmouth have ranged from a low of {{convert|15|\u00b0F}} in January to a high of {{convert|85|\u00b0F}} in July, although a record low of {{convert|-27|\u00b0F}} was recorded in February 1905 and a record high of {{convert|110|\u00b0F}} was recorded in July 1936.  Average monthly precipitation ranged from {{convert|1.62|in}} in January to {{convert|4.33|in}} in July.<ref name=\"weather\"/>\n\n===Adjacent counties===\n* [[Mercer County, Illinois|Mercer County]] (north)\n* [[Knox County, Illinois|Knox County]] (east)\n* [[Fulton County, Illinois|Fulton County]] (southeast)\n* [[McDonough County, Illinois|McDonough County]] (south)\n* [[Henderson County, Illinois|Henderson County]] (west)\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1830= 308\n|1840= 6739\n|1850= 8176\n|1860= 18336\n|1870= 23174\n|1880= 22933\n|1890= 21281\n|1900= 23163\n|1910= 23313\n|1920= 21488\n|1930= 21745\n|1940= 21286\n|1950= 21981\n|1960= 21587\n|1970= 21595\n|1980= 21943\n|1990= 19181\n|2000= 18735\n|2010= 17707\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=17032\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=November 2, 2019}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=July 9, 2014}}</ref><br />1790-1960<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapserver.lib.virginia.edu|title=Historical Census Browser|publisher=University of Virginia Library|accessdate=July 9, 2014}}</ref> 1900-1990<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/il190090.txt|title=Population of Counties by Decennial Census: 1900 to 1990|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=July 9, 2014}}</ref><br />1990-2000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/cen2000/briefs/phc-t4/tables/tab02.pdf|title=Census 2000 PHC-T-4. Ranking Tables for Counties: 1990 and 2000|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=July 9, 2014}}</ref> 2010-2013<ref name=\"QF\"/>\n}}\n\nAt the [[2010 United States Census]], there were 17,707&nbsp;people, 6,918&nbsp;households and 4,617&nbsp;families residing in the county.<ref name=\"census-dp1\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/0500000US17187\n  |title=DP-1 Profile of General Population and Housing Characteristics: 2010 Demographic Profile Data\n  |accessdate=July 12, 2015\n  |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]\n  |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213032711/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/0500000US17187\n  |archive-date=February 13, 2020\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}</ref> The population density was {{convert|32.6|PD/sqmi}}. There were 7,682 housing units at an average density of {{convert|14.2|/sqmi}}.<ref name=\"census-density\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/GCTPH1.CY10/0500000US17187\n  |accessdate=July 12, 2015\n  |title=Population, Housing Units, Area, and Density: 2010 - County\n  |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]\n  |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212201137/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/GCTPH1.CY10/0500000US17187\n  |archive-date=February 12, 2020\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}</ref> The racial makeup of the county was 91.3% white, 1.7% black or African American, 0.5% Asian, 0.2% American Indian, 0.1% Pacific islander, 4.5% from other races, and 1.6% from two or more races. Those of Hispanic or Latino origin made up 8.4% of the population.<ref name=\"census-dp1\"/> In terms of ancestry, 25.2% were [[Germans|German]], 14.7% were [[Irish people|Irish]], 11.3% were [[English people|English]], 10.0% were [[Swedes|Swedish]], and 5.5% were [[Americans|American]].<ref name=\"census-dp2\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP02/0500000US17187\n  |title=DP02 SELECTED SOCIAL CHARACTERISTICS IN THE UNITED STATES \u2013 2006-2010 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates\n  |accessdate=July 12, 2015\n  |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]\n  |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213011927/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP02/0500000US17187\n  |archive-date=February 13, 2020\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}</ref>\n\nOf the 6,918&nbsp;households, 29.6% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 52.2% were married couples living together, 9.7% had a female householder with no husband present, 33.3% were non-families, and 28.2% of all households were made up of individuals. The average household size was 2.40 and the average family size was 2.91. The median age was 39.6 years.<ref name=\"census-dp1\"/>\n\nThe [[median household income]] was $41,636 and the median family income was $49,623. Males had a median income of $40,289 and females $25,460. The per capita incomewas $20,047. About 11.0% of families and 13.4% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 18.1% of those under age 18 and 10.6% of those age 65 or over.<ref name=\"census-dp3\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP03/0500000US17187\n  |title=DP03 SELECTED ECONOMIC CHARACTERISTICS \u2013 2006-2010 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates\n  |accessdate=July 12, 2015\n  |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]\n  |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213010952/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP03/0500000US17187\n  |archive-date=February 13, 2020\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nWarren County is located in [[Illinois's 17th congressional district|Illinois's 17th Congressional District]] and is currently represented by Democrat [[Cheri Bustos]]. For the [[Illinois House of Representatives]], the county is split between the 93rd district, currently represented by Republican [[Norine Hammond]], and the 94th district, currently represented by [[Randy Frese]]. The county is located in the 47th district of the [[Illinois Senate]], and is currently represented by Republican [[Jil Tracy]].\n\nIn presidential elections, Warren County voted for the Republican Party's candidate in every election from [[1936 United States presidential election|1936]] through 1988, often by a wide margin. From 1992\u20132012, the contest in Warren County was more competitive, with the Democratic Party's candidate  winning four out of six times.\n{{Hidd