loyd Township, Warren County, Illinois|Floyd]]\n* [[Greenbush Township, Warren County, Illinois|Greenbush]]\n* [[Hale Township, Warren County, Illinois|Hale]]\n* [[Kelly Township, Warren County, Illinois|Kelly]]\n* [[Lenox Township, Warren County, Illinois|Lenox]]\n* [[Monmouth Township, Warren County, Illinois|Monmouth]]\n* [[Point Pleasant Township, Warren County, Illinois|Point Pleasant]]\n* [[Roseville Township, Warren County, Illinois|Roseville]]\n* [[Spring Grove Township, Warren County, Illinois|Spring Grove]]\n* [[Sumner Township, Warren County, Illinois|Sumner]]\n* [[Swan Township, Warren County, Illinois|Swan]]\n* [[Tompkins Township, Warren County, Illinois|Tompkins]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Warren County, Illinois]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Geographic Location\n|Centre    = Warren County, Illinois\n|North     = [[Mercer County, Illinois|Mercer County]]\n|Northeast =\n|East      = [[Knox County, Illinois|Knox County]]\n|Southeast = [[Fulton County, Illinois|Fulton County]]\n|South     = [[McDonough County, Illinois|McDonough County]]\n|Southwest =\n|West      = [[Henderson County, Illinois|Henderson County]]\n|Northwest =\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080709045407/http://www.9thjudicial.org/Warren/indexWarren.htm Warren County Circuit Court]\n* [http://www.usgennet.org/usa/il/county/warren/ Welcome to Warren Co., IL AHGP]\n\n{{Warren County, Illinois}}\n{{Central-Illinois}}\n{{Illinois}}\n\n{{Coord|40.85|-90.61|display=title|type:adm2nd_region:US-IL_source:UScensus1990}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Illinois counties]]\n[[Category:1825 establishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1825]]\n[[Category:Warren County, Illinois| ]]\n[[Category:Galesburg, Illinois micropolitan area]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|County in Illinois}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox U.S. county|\n county  = Warren County|\n state = Illinois |\n seal = |\n founded = 1825|\n seat wl= Monmouth |\n largest city wl = Monmouth|\n area_total_sq_mi = 543 |\n area_land_sq_mi = 542 |\n area_water_sq_mi = 0.6 |\n area percentage = 0.1 |\n population_as_of = 2010|\n population_total = 17707 |\n pop_est_as_of = 2018 |\n population_est = 17032 |\n population_density_sq_mi = auto |\n web = www.warrencountyil.com|\n ex image = Warren County Courthouse in Monmouth.jpg|\n ex image cap = [[Warren County Courthouse (Illinois)|Warren County Courthouse]] in Monmouth\n| district = 17th\n| time zone = Central\n| named for= [[Joseph Warren]]\n}}\n\n'''Warren County''' is a [[County (United States)|county]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Illinois]]. According to the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]], it had a population of 17,707.<ref name=\"QF\">{{cite web|title=State & County QuickFacts|url=http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/17/17187.html|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=July 9, 2014}}</ref> Its [[county seat]] is [[Monmouth, Illinois|Monmouth]].<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx|accessdate=2011-06-07|title=Find a County|publisher=National Association of Counties}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nWarren County was organized in 1825 out of [[Pike County, Illinois|Pike County]] which consisted of all portions of the state north and west of the Illinois River before 1825. [[Henderson County, Illinois|Henderson County]] was formed in 1841 from the western area of Warren County.\n\nWarren County was named for Dr. [[Joseph Warren]], killed at the [[Battle of Bunker Hill]] in 1775. He is believed to have been the first officer to die in the [[American Revolutionary War|Revolutionary War]].\n\nThe current courthouse, constructed of red Portage stone, was completed in 1895.\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Warren County Illinois 1825.png|Warren County from the time of its creation to 1831\nFile:Warren County Illinois 1831.png|Between 1831 and 1835, Mercer County was temporarily attached to Warren until it could organize its own county government.<ref>White, Jesse. ''[http://www.cyberdriveillinois.com/publications/pdf_publications/ipub15.pdf Origin and Evolution of Illinois Counties]''. State of Illinois, March 2010.</ref>\nFile:Warren_County,_Illinois_-_1835.png|Warren County between 1835 and 1841\nFile:Warren County Illinois 1841.png|Warren County in 1841, reduced to its current borders by the creation of Henderson County \n</gallery>\n\n==Geography==\nAccording to the [[U.S. Census Bureau]], the county has a total area of {{convert|543|sqmi}}, of which {{convert|542|sqmi}} is land and {{convert|0.6|sqmi}} (0.1%) is water.<ref name=\"census-density\"/>\n\n===Climate and weather===\n{{climate chart\n|[[Monmouth, Illinois]]\n|15|31|1.62\n|21|37|1.72\n|30|49|2.85\n|41|63|3.76\n|51|73|4.27\n|60|81|4.26\n|64|85|4.33\n|62|83|4.02\n|54|77|3.45\n|43|65|2.97\n|32|49|2.74\n|20|35|2.32\n|float=right\n|units=imperial\n|clear=both\n|source=The Weather Channel<ref name=\"weather\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.weather.com/weather/wxclimatology/monthly/graph/USIL0791\n  |title=Monthly Averages for Monmouth, Illinois\n  |accessdate=2011-01-27\n  |publisher=The Weather Channel\n}}</ref>}}\nIn recent years, average temperatures in the county seat of Monmouth have ranged from a low of {{convert|15|\u00b0F}} in January to a high of {{convert|85|\u00b0F}} in July, although a record low of {{convert|-27|\u00b0F}} was recorded in February 1905 and a record high of {{convert|110|\u00b0F}} was recorded in July 1936.  Average monthly precipitation ranged from {{convert|1.62|in}} in January to {{convert|4.33|in}} in July.<ref name=\"weather\"/>\n\n===Adjacent counties===\n*[[Mercer County, Illinois|Mercer County]] (north)\n*[[Knox County, Illinois|Knox County]] (east)\n*[[Fulton County, Illinois|Fulton County]] (southeast)\n*[[McDonough County, Illinois|McDonough County]] (south)\n*[[Henderson County, Illinois|Henderson County]] (west)\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1830= 308\n|1840= 6739\n|1850= 8176\n|1860= 18336\n|1870= 23174\n|1880= 22933\n|1890= 21281\n|1900= 23163\n|1910= 23313\n|1920= 21488\n|1930= 21745\n|1940= 21286\n|1950= 21981\n|1960= 21587\n|1970= 21595\n|1980= 21943\n|1990= 19181\n|2000= 18735\n|2010= 17707\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=17032\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=November 2, 2019}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=July 9, 2014}}</ref><br />1790-1960<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapserver.lib.virginia.edu|title=Historical Census Browser|publisher=University of Virginia Library|accessdate=July 9, 2014}}</ref> 1900-1990<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/il190090.txt|title=Population of Counties by Decennial Census: 1900 to 1990|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=July 9, 2014}}</ref><br />1990-2000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/cen2000/briefs/phc-t4/tables/tab02.pdf|title=Census 2000 PHC-T-4. Ranking Tables for Counties: 1990 and 2000|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=July 9, 2014}}</ref> 2010-2013<ref name=\"QF\"/>\n}}\n\nAt the [[2010 United States Census]], there were 17,707&nbsp;people, 6,918&nbsp;households and 4,617&nbsp;families residing in the county.<ref name=\"census-dp1\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/0500000US17187\n  |title=DP-1 Profile of General Population and Housing Characteristics: 2010 Demographic Profile Data\n  |accessdate=July 12, 2015\n  |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]\n  |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213032711/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/0500000US17187\n  |archive-date=February 13, 2020\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}</ref> The population density was {{convert|32.6|PD/sqmi}}. There were 7,682 housing units at an average density of {{convert|14.2|/sqmi}}.<ref name=\"census-density\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/GCTPH1.CY10/0500000US17187\n  |accessdate=July 12, 2015\n  |title=Population, Housing Units, Area, and Density: 2010 - County\n  |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]\n  |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212201137/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/GCTPH1.CY10/0500000US17187\n  |archive-date=February 12, 2020\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}</ref> The racial makeup of the county was 91.3% white, 1.7% black or African American, 0.5% Asian, 0.2% American Indian, 0.1% Pacific islander, 4.5% from other races, and 1.6% from two or more races. Those of Hispanic or Latino origin made up 8.4% of the population.<ref name=\"census-dp1\"/> In terms of ancestry, 25.2% were [[Germans|German]], 14.7% were [[Irish people|Irish]], 11.3% were [[English people|English]], 10.0% were [[Swedes|Swedish]], and 5.5% were [[Americans|American]].<ref name=\"census-dp2\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP02/0500000US17187\n  |title=DP02 SELECTED SOCIAL CHARACTERISTICS IN THE UNITED STATES \u2013 2006-2010 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates\n  |accessdate=July 12, 2015\n  |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]\n  |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213011927/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP02/0500000US17187\n  |archive-date=February 13, 2020\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}</ref>\n\nOf the 6,918&nbsp;households, 29.6% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 52.2% were married couples living together, 9.7% had a female householder with no husband present, 33.3% were non-families, and 28.2% of all households were made up of individuals. The average household size was 2.40 and the average family size was 2.91. The median age was 39.6 years.<ref name=\"census-dp1\"/>\n\nThe [[median household income]] was $41,636 and the median family income was $49,623. Males had a median income of $40,289 and females $25,460. The per capita incomewas $20,047. About 11.0% of families and 13.4% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 18.1% of those under age 18 and 10.6% of those age 65 or over.<ref name=\"census-dp3\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP03/0500000US17187\n  |title=DP03 SELECTED ECONOMIC CHARACTERISTICS \u2013 2006-2010 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates\n  |accessdate=July 12, 2015\n  |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]\n  |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213010952/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP03/0500000US17187\n  |archive-date=February 13, 2020\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nWarren County is located in [[Illinois's 17th congressional district|Illinois's 17th Congressional District]] and is currently represented by Democrat [[Cheri Bustos]]. For the [[Illinois House of Representatives]], the county is split between the 93rd district, currently represented by Republican [[Norine Hammond]], and the 94th district, currently represented by [[Randy Frese]]. The county is located in the 47th district of the [[Illinois Senate]], and is currently represented by Republican [[Jil Tracy]].\n\nIn presidential elections, Warren County voted for the Republican Party's candidate in every election from [[1936 United States presidential election|1936]] through 1988, often by a wide margin. From 1992\u20132012, the contest in Warren County was more competitive, with the Democratic Party's candidate  winning four out of six times.\n{{Hidden begin\n|titlestyle = background:#ccccff;\n|title      = Presidential elections results\n}}\n{| align=\"center\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"float: